snippet.textDisplay:
I made the mistake of buying something that hadn’t been looked after. I was 19 years old 3rd year carpenter saw a 79 for $30,000 with 150,000km on it I went and viewed it he had steam cleaned it and it looked brand new. No oil leaks.. nothing, and it drove well. I wanted to do it on my own so I didn’t tell anyone just bought it. (Being 19 you don’t know shit about life, they don’t teach you about these things in school. 8 months down the track I have spent $10,000+ on fixing the thing and it’s still not 100% I’ve learnt a lot of valuable life lessons. Yeah a lot of people say you should have got it checked (it’s easy to say all that) but I trusted the road worthy certificate it came with.

It had
- cracked front diff coil mounts
- sump wasn’t sealed properly
- all uni joints were worn

snippet.textDisplay:
I bought a beast from Nation Motors in Dandenong, I bought the newest vehicle with higher ks for my money 11k. Little did I know after I bought it the loud pop I heard was a champagne bottle popping in his office, the vehicle was fine for over a week then the starter motor went, his 3rd party 1 year warranty that he threw in with the vehicle will cover everything, but it didn't and the warranty lady who called me was laughing when she said great news, they won't cover it because it's not their problem ( National warranty ) $1300 replaced it. A week after that it breaks down $350 for some modules and a broken water sensor. I did all the tests before I gave my hard earned money. 2 months later the computer went $3500, I soon sold it for $6200,
$11000 + $5150 = $16150
Sold for $6200 just to get rid of it and I told the new owner everything I went through and that I couldn't wait to see it gone
$16150 - $6200 = $9950 out of pocket, it only took me around 5 years to save up. All I can say is look out for a dealer warranty and always get a full pit inspection from RACV or RACQ or who ever is your biggest roadside assistance and insurance company, if they offer you a third party warranty tell them no thanks, stick with dealer warranty and not some dodgy scammers that are happy to peddle you a dud warranty!
So many warranty claims are maid but very few are honoured by the warranty company unless you have time to fight tooth and nail. With high tech vehicles it's almost impossible to see any problems when it's usually electronic and computers.
I felt so bad selling it but I did everything in my power to rectify it but some vehicles should never have been allowed in the road in the first place!

snippet.textDisplay:
I feel attacked by this vid. Getting our 2001 Prado ready for market soon, dust all through it cos it used to live on a gravel road and shit dual battery wiring cos they didn't have everything transistorised and wrapped in shiny plastic in 2002, but it's a good old car and I reckon it'll kick on for longer than the hilux in this vid (just kick a lot slower).


Here's another one to look out for, mismatched shocks, springs, CVs etc. They've been out and broken something and not replaced the set - the odd one out might be about to let go. If the car's warm when you get there they might be hiding a shitty noise on startup, so tell 'em the vehicle is going to be cold started or you'll walk. Check battery/alt/regulator with checking DCV before & after a quick drive. And if you can see an fluid pan and neatly arranged work bench on the seller's property, don't hang everything on the service history! Some blokes I know I'd trust the bloke more than the Toyota dealer!

snippet.textDisplay: I scored a 2006 E53 X5 3.0 diesel for $3k here in NZ, they usually go for nearly triple the price. It had done 350k when I got it not even 6 months ago. First owner was doing a 300k round trip every day for 6 days a week, constant hot, open road running. Full service history until the guy I bought it off, never been crashed, has been used for towing. It has cost me less than $600 in parts so far (including a full service, air and fuel filters), and I have done nearly 15k in 6 months without an issue. Moral of the story - higher k's, even in older cars, isn't so much a problem if they are longer distance and everything hot running. People get put off cars/4WD's because of high k's when they shouldn't be.
